@@eShadowmere -- Harbor Warden Institutional Failure Analysis@@N

The @@yHarbor Wardens@@N study Shadowmere the way navigators study
shipwrecks: not to mourn, but to @@ylearn what killed it@@N.

Shadowmere was a frontier march extending @@yMidgaard's@@N law into
unstable territory. Its mandate: guard transit, tax goods, process
the dead, keep records. These are @@gfunctions we perform every
day@@N. Shadowmere was, in its founding purpose, a city that could
have been our cousin.

Then came the @@rPlague Mandate@@N, and everything the Strandline
Compact was built to prevent.

Emergency directives authorized forced quarantines, cremation powers,
and suspension of lineage appeals. @@rTemporary became permanent.@@N In
Mafdet, emergency harbor closures require Strandline Compact review
within ten days. The chain can be raised under threat, but must be
@@ylowered under attestation@@N: a sworn statement reviewed by all three
blocs. No single authority keeps emergency powers beyond the emergency.

Shadowmere had no such constraint. Crown envoys, Compact wardens,
Temple delegates, and March commanders each refused to yield. The
@@rLast Bell Crisis@@N -- three contradictory decrees in one night --
is the exact failure mode the Dual-Attestation Protocol prevents.
Two independent verifications. If they contradict, @@rneither
proceeds@@N until reconciled. One authority issuing unchecked orders
is how ports become prisons.

The @@dBlight Hydrology Doctrine@@N is infrastructure contamination:
runoff routed through burial districts, sealed crypts flooded from
below, low fields becoming toxic wetlands. The Quarantine Ledger
names this @@rprocess waste becoming environmental hazard@@N. Our harbor
maintains strict separation between ballast discharge, cargo
handling, and healing-house drainage. @@dContamination travels
through infrastructure.@@N

Shadowmere's five factions -- the @@WOathbound March@@N executing
obsolete orders, the @@rCrimson Household@@N claiming bloodline, the
@@dBinder Collegium@@N treating souls as ledger entries, the @@rGallows
Syndicate@@N monetizing execution, and the @@eFen-Adapted Remnants@@N
beyond governance -- are @@rfive forms of broken attestation@@N. The
Shrine of the First Claw would recognize none of their oaths.

The Harbor Wardens' summary is carved above our chain house gate:
@@d"Orders stamped, witnessed, sealed, and wrong."@@N

That line -- the oldest entry in our failure study collection --
reminds every Warden: @@yprocess without accountability is the most
dangerous weapon a city can build against itself.@@N
